(1): Baboons with the solar boat; (2); A priest offering to Min, Isis, Nephthys, Anubis, Ptah and Horus (or Ra?); (3): The souls of Pe and Nekhen, with a bull. On A, the paint has worn badly, but there are traces of purple on the faces and chest of the sphinxes, on the band along the wing at the base of the feathers, and for dots in loops and corners of the volute tree; on B, purple on alternate feathers of eagle and the band at their base, following incised lines on breast of partridge, for alternate dots of rosette.

description.value: Fragmentary black-figure painted pottery situla. Designs originally black, on drab panels on the neck, with purple accessories and incised lines.  (a) Bellerophon riding on Pegasos to right, wearing a short chiton, and seated between the wings of Pegasos, with a long spear in right hand. His head is missing.   (b) The Chimaera with head of lion, body of goat, and tail in form of a serpent, standing to left. Below all round is a large fan-pattern formed of half-rosettes, alternating with lotus-flowers of five pointed leaves, in two bands. The figures have been painted in black on a creamy-white slip, but the black is almost entirely worn away.

description.value: Situla. Designs in black on buff panels on the neck, with incised lines and accessories of purple.  (a) In the centre, a winged male figure ending in a serpent, bearded, with short purple chiton, the head turned to right, holding a serpent in either hand; the wings start from his breast. The name of Typhon, or Boreas, has been suggested for this figure. At his right side is a plant with stiff leaves, and in the field crosses and dots. On either side is a square with borders of rosettes formed of discs surrounded by dots; in each square is a diamond filled in with a diaper-pattern.  (b) In the centre, an erect male figure to right with wings starting from his breast, and short purple chiton , apparently letting loose two birds of prey upon a hare which stands on its hind-legs to right in front of him. Behind the hare stands a larger bird to right, and in the field above is a tettix (cicada?), also crosses and dots, as in (a). If the figure on the other side is Boreas, this may be one of his two sons, Zetes and Calais.  On either side is a square, as on (a). The one on the left has a border of rosettes, as before; in it is a star of four points, shaded, with segments of circles and rows of dots filling up the angles; in the field, crosses and dots. The square on the right has borders of rosettes above and below, and down each side a chevron-pattern interspersed with dots; in it is a diamond filled in with diaper-pattern; in the field, patterns of crosses and dots, and in the angles of the square, segments of circles and rows of dots.

On either side is a square with borders of rosettes formed of discs surrounded by dots; in each square is a diamond filled in with a diaper-pattern.  (b) In the centre, an erect male figure to right with wings starting from his breast, and short purple chiton , apparently letting loose two birds of prey upon a hare which stands on its hind-legs to right in front of him. Behind the hare stands a larger bird to right, and in the field above is a grasshopper, also crosses and dots, as in (a). If the figure on the other side is Boreas, this may be one of his two sons, Zetes and Calais.  On either side is a square, as on (a). The one on the left has a border of rosettes, as before; in it is a star of four points, shaded, with segments of circles and rows of dots filling up the angles; in the field, crosses and dots. The square on the right has borders of rosettes above and below, and down each side a chevron-pattern interspersed with dots; in it is a diamond filled in with diaper-pattern; in the field, patterns of crosses and dots, and in the angles of the square, segments of circles and rows of dots.

description.value: A man's skull-cap. Made of four equal-sized segments of green satin silk cloth. Couched all over with circular motifs, laid on the diagonal, using gold-coloured metal wrapped thread with a sequin in the centre. Lines of looped thread at the edges, emphasising the cap's four sections. A strip of red tabby woollen cloth at bottom edge, couched with a meandering line and similar circular motifs as before. Unlined; cloth used as facing visible: cream and purple printed cotton cloth.   A man's (?) hat; cylindrical; made of mid-brown satin silk cloth. Silver-coloured metal sequins (encircled with silver-coloured metal-wrapped thread) couched on the diagonal on top and sides. Mid-top has eight-petalled floral motif and edge of crown and base of sides have ornate passementerie trimming, also made with sequins and metal thread. Rim has red tabby silk (?) piping. Hat lined with cream, red, green and blue tabby cotton striped cloth.  A woman's (?) small cap; circular crown, with short sides. Ground made from purple silk velvet cloth. Crown embroidered with a large floral motif: six stems with leaves radiating from an eight-petalled flower. Worked in gold-coloured metal wire over a padded base. A meandering floral and foliage motif, worked in the same manner and materials, decorates the sides. Most of the remaining ground cover in small sequins. Two ornate tassels, made with different forms of metal wire, stitched to centre top. Embroidered on front of cap is the Arabic word for God. (Colour of metal wire different to remainder.) Cap lined with tabby lilac silk cloth (much damaged).
